<DOC><DOCNO> AP880323-0069 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0716EST</FILEID><FIRST>d a PM-BRF--IssuesPoll     03-23 0177</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Issues Poll,0180</SECOND><HEAD>Poll: Americans Would Rather Not Hear About Iran-Contra Scandal</HEAD><DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Many Americans say they have heard enoughabout the Iran-Contra affair and unrest in Israel's occupiedterritories, a national poll found.   A Tampa Tribune-Gallup Poll of 1,211 registered voters,conducted by telephone between March 10-12 and released today,found that 64 percent wanted to hear less about the Iran-Contrascandal. Only 29 percent wanted more information about the affair.   On social unrest in Israel, 42 percent wanted to know more and47 percent wanted less information, according to the poll, whichhad a 3 percent margin of error.   The poll also found that most Americans care more about issuessuch as drug abuse, long-term health care, quality education andaid to the homeless.   Of those polled, 84 percent said they wanted to hear more aboutbattling illegal drugs. At least two-thirds of the polled voterswanted more information about efforts to fight AIDS, makingAmerican businesses more competitive with foreign imports andnegotiating arms control agreements with the Soviet Union.</TEXT></DOC>